{"name":"Follower","permission":{"default":0,"RrWQxiSTW954To8L":3},"type":"background","data":{"description":"<p>The character has a loyal follower, such as a dedicated servant, a devoted disciple or a lovesick admirer. The follower is sincerely loyal to the character, serving freely and more dutifully than a hired servant would, willingly endangering her own life if it might ensure the character&rsquo;s survival. The reason for this devotion must be established before the game begins with the Arbiter&rsquo;s approval. The follower might owe the character her life as a blood-debt, depend on the character for their future prosperity or survival, or view the character as a prophet or religious leader. Forced allegiance is not uncommon, so a character may even have threatened the follower into homage - create a story which fits with the character&rsquo;s personality and backstory. The Arbiter will create the follower NPC. You may purchase this Background multiple times and thereby gain several followers.</p>","cost":6},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"12IiZsjJU94STQzV"}
{"name":"Local","permission":{"default":0,"RrWQxiSTW954To8L":3},"type":"background","data":{"description":"<p>The character is very familiar with a geographical area or culture, knowing the regional setting, landscape, society and history in great detail. The chosen area can be any clearly defined location or culture, such as a Llyhn district or a tribal people from a distant world.</p>\n<p>The character is either a native or has spent considerable time integrating with the culture, essentially merging with it. The character rarely gets lost anywhere in the area, has near-encyclopaedic knowledge of it, and will be familiar with a great part of the population. Characters gain +1 to all direction, lore, reputation and response rolls when in or with regards to the chosen region or culture.</p>","cost":2},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"14C0n6FM5ZCGGYbE"}
{"name":"Status (III)","permission":{"default":0,"RrWQxiSTW954To8L":3},"type":"background","data":{"description":"<p>Your character has managed to gain a certain amount of status and level of authority within a guild, group or faction in Llyhn. This can be an official status (such as mercenary captain or high priest) or it can be informal recognition by her peers, granting her words great weight within the group. The player must specify the group within which status is held, what the status is and how it was achieved, subject to Arbiter&rsquo;s approval.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>(III): </strong><strong>The character is part of the </strong><strong>leadership within the group.</strong></p>","cost":9},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"3i6z020LlhjhaEwY"}
{"name":"Resources (I)","permission":{"default":0,"RrWQxiSTW954To8L":3},"type":"background","data":{"description":"<p>The character has an extraordinary source of income and a substantial amount of resources are available no matter which caste she belongs to. There are many ways to acquire resources or income in Llyhn, both through legitimate or prohibited means. Dealing in contraband, selling merchandise or having inherited wealth are some of the possibilities.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>(I):&nbsp;</strong><strong>D12x10 copper Dhin starting funds </strong><strong>and assets worth 500 copper Dhins.</strong></p>","cost":3},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"4WsAGNQmEmSbclqE"}
{"name":"Voidmarked","permission":{"default":0,"RrWQxiSTW954To8L":3},"type":"background","data":{"description":"<p>Human, but not entirely human; Voidmarked characters have been affected by the effects beyond the Veil of Cosmic reality in one way or another. There are several variants of Voidmarked, which are distinctly different from each other: Those who have been influenced by the strange warping effects in Llyhn or from Void-travelling, the offspring of human and Daimonic beings, and those few who have attained ascension. Because of their diverse backgrounds or parentage Voidmarked vary considerably in appearance and temperament. Those that retain a generally human form usually display several outlandish characteristics such as strange eyes, odd complexion or other faintly non-human characteristics.</p>\n<p>Voidmarked characters may have regular and esoteric attributes and acquire Mystic powers.</p>","cost":2},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"9qm7XjvhZ9eJt1ZO"}
{"name":"Residence (II)","permission":{"default":0,"RrWQxiSTW954To8L":3},"type":"background","data":{"description":"<p>The character possesses a hovel, house or other dwelling. The residence is a place where the character can feel secure, avoid prying eyes and keep her valuables and other possessions safe. The location, layout, size and security or secrecy of the residence must be determined before the game commences.</p>\n<p>Residences can take many shapes and forms, ranging from a comfortable the streets of the Kimah district her entire life and residence to dark and damp underground dumps.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>(II): T</strong><strong>he residence </strong><strong>consists of one decent room or two smaller </strong><strong>rooms with which up to three people may </strong><strong>occupy, although barely at that.</strong></p>","cost":6},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"A7ShdgnDcVC5VI7v"}
{"name":"Educated","permission":{"default":0,"RrWQxiSTW954To8L":3},"type":"background","data":{"description":"<p>The character is educated, has learned civilised manners and is somewhat versed in academic arts such as philosophy, languages and history.</p>\n<p>Due to the character&rsquo;s obvious schooling, eloquence and etiquette he or she gains +1 to reactions when encountering high castes, educated or scholarly people. Furthermore, the character only suffers a -1 penalty to lore skills he or she is untrained in.</p>","cost":2},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"AD00NUdWX8LkwtgR"}
{"name":"Caste (III)","permission":{"default":0,"RrWQxiSTW954To8L":3},"type":"background","data":{"description":"<p>The social hierarchy of the Eternal City is divided into classes determined not only by species and birth, but also by wealth and power. The classes are grouped into low, common and high castes. The higher a character&rsquo;s caste, the more wealth, influence and resources she is likely to command. Outside this system are the casteless, a segment not considered part of the social hierarchy. Characters always begin as casteless but can gain ranks within the low and common castes by spending character points. Different castes interact following strict social conventions and codes of conduct.</p>\n<p>As players spend points to acquire caste rankings, the character&rsquo;s starting funds and social standing increases.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>(II): </strong><strong>MUATI (6): Mainly artisans, tradesmen and merchants, </strong><strong>Ummani are among the common castes in Llyhn. This caste </strong><strong>enjoys several privileges and can move freely around some </strong><strong>of the upper districts of the city.</strong></p>","cost":6},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"H8Z5zeKn2g2cX65D"}
{"name":"Reputation (II)","permission":{"default":0,"RrWQxiSTW954To8L":3},"type":"background","data":{"description":"<p>The character is well-known. The player decides whether the reputation is based on infamy, acclaim or another type of prominence, subject to the Arbiter&rsquo;s approval. A reputation generally works favourably, as renowned characters often use their fame to get special privileges but may cause difficulties when acting discretely.</p>\n<p>As reputation increases the character is known to a wider part of a population and the likelihood of beneficial privileges and advantages increases, but so does the number of sycophants and social parasites.</p>\n<p>The character counts as having an Awe ranking of 7 towards the people who are aware of his or her reputation.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>(II): </strong><strong>The character </strong><strong>is known in wider circles of a few hundred individuals and </strong><strong>may add a +1 modifier when socialising within this group.</strong></p>","cost":4},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"LMVsYpwiknvzXUtp"}
{"name":"Mentor","permission":{"default":0,"RrWQxiSTW954To8L":3},"type":"background","data":{"description":"<p>The character has a mentor; a teacher, advisor and counsellor on whom she can rely.</p>\n<p>The mentor will likely be someone wise or learned, who can impart knowledge to the character in times of need. The mentor may even function as a protector and helper within her sphere of influence. Beyond giving advice, the mentor will likely put her own network at the disposal of the character, possibly even contributing resources, contacts and influence to the character. The mentor is typically also the patron or matron of the character.</p>","cost":6},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"Mscq4jFDH7gHjifk"}
{"name":"Residence (I)","permission":{"default":0,"RrWQxiSTW954To8L":3},"type":"background","data":{"description":"<p>The character possesses a hovel, house or other dwelling. The residence is a place where the character can feel secure, avoid prying eyes and keep her valuables and other possessions safe. The location, layout, size and security or secrecy of the residence must be determined before the game commences.</p>\n<p>Residences can take many shapes and forms, ranging from a comfortable the streets of the Kimah district her entire life and residence to dark and damp underground dumps.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>(I):&nbsp;</strong><strong>The dwelling is a small </strong><strong>chamber or other space with room for </strong><strong>one occupant.</strong></p>","cost":3},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"S1lGr4ieagxExmPq"}
{"name":"Resources (II)","permission":{"default":0,"RrWQxiSTW954To8L":3},"type":"background","data":{"description":"<p>The character has an extraordinary source of income and a substantial amount of resources are available no matter which caste she belongs to. There are many ways to acquire resources or income in Llyhn, both through legitimate or prohibited means. Dealing in contraband, selling merchandise or having inherited wealth are some of the possibilities.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>(II): </strong><strong>D12x25 copper Dhin starting funds </strong><strong>and assets worth 1000 copper Dhins.</strong></p>","cost":6},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"TupeVaUT3kGpSv78"}
{"name":"Status (I)","permission":{"default":0,"RrWQxiSTW954To8L":3},"type":"background","data":{"description":"<p>Your character has managed to gain a certain amount of status and level of authority within a guild, group or faction in Llyhn. This can be an official status (such as mercenary captain or high priest) or it can be informal recognition by her peers, granting her words great weight within the group. The player must specify the group within which status is held, what the status is and how it was achieved, subject to Arbiter&rsquo;s approval.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>(I): The character has limited authority within the group but is above regular members.</strong></p>","cost":3},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"UUNtPKQR5KXUoRtu"}
{"name":"Caste (I)","permission":{"default":0,"RrWQxiSTW954To8L":3},"type":"background","data":{"description":"<p>The social hierarchy of the Eternal City is divided into classes determined not only by species and birth, but also by wealth and power. The classes are grouped into low, common and high castes. The higher a character&rsquo;s caste, the more wealth, influence and resources she is likely to command. Outside this system are the casteless, a segment not considered part of the social hierarchy. Characters always begin as casteless but can gain ranks within the low and common castes by spending character points. Different castes interact following strict social conventions and codes of conduct.</p>\n<p>As players spend points to acquire caste rankings, the character&rsquo;s starting funds and social standing increases.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>(I): BALTU - This caste enjoys few privileges and is largely associated with unskilled labourers and slaves of negligible importance. Baltu are at the very bottom of society and largely confined to the slum areas of the Eternal City - unless in chains.</strong></p>","cost":1},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"X1fHQnDgQNOlnBZK"}
{"name":"Contacts (III)","permission":{"default":0,"RrWQxiSTW954To8L":3},"type":"background","data":{"description":"<p>The character has a well-established network of reliable contacts. They can be from a variety of worlds, species and walks of life. Each contact has a specific area of knowledge and field of expertise within which he can gain access to information or further connections. The network can include old acquaintances or people the character manipulates or bribes. Which contacts are available at any given time can be resolved in various ways - either during the game at a player&rsquo;s request or the Arbiter&rsquo;s discretion, by prior agreement between player and Arbiter or based on the character&rsquo;s history.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>(III): </strong><strong>The character has a significant network of </strong><strong>contacts in a wide array of areas who can supply her with an </strong><strong>abundance of information.</strong></p>","cost":6},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"XT9wsX8gB0HpYRtF"}
{"name":"Caste (II)","permission":{"default":0,"RrWQxiSTW954To8L":3},"type":"background","data":{"description":"<p>The social hierarchy of the Eternal City is divided into classes determined not only by species and birth, but also by wealth and power. The classes are grouped into low, common and high castes. The higher a character&rsquo;s caste, the more wealth, influence and resources she is likely to command. Outside this system are the casteless, a segment not considered part of the social hierarchy. Characters always begin as casteless but can gain ranks within the low and common castes by spending character points. Different castes interact following strict social conventions and codes of conduct.</p>\n<p>As players spend points to acquire caste rankings, the character&rsquo;s starting funds and social standing increases.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>(II): S</strong><strong>HAHRVAH - Skilled labourers, farmers, peasants and </strong><strong>fishers who do not own their resources or tools make up this </strong><strong>caste. This group is part of the low castes.</strong></p>","cost":3},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"byvK7n1C2OBafLxF"}
{"name":"Allies (II)","permission":{"default":0,"RrWQxiSTW954To8L":3},"type":"background","data":{"description":"<p>Your character has one or more allies who may be able to provide information, resources, contacts or other support to your character. Allies are often family, people your character has befriended or factions/guilds that your character has worked with in the past.</p>\n<p>Allies are usually trustworthy and will help your character if possible, but remember they also have agendas, priorities and responsibilities of their own. Alliances are give-and-take relations, and an over-exploited ally will not remain helpful for long. Allies are also likely to request the help of characters on occasion. Moreover, the activities of characters and their allies will influence each others&rsquo; reputations if the affiliation is openly known.</p>\n<p>While the player should make the initial proposal about the relationship and particulars of an ally, the Arbiter has the final word regarding allies&rsquo; power, influence and background.</p>\n<p><strong>(II): Two lowly allies, or one of moderate power and authority.</strong></p>","cost":4},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"cY4sMYYuda8Kk5yT"}
{"name":"Caste (0)","permission":{"default":0,"RrWQxiSTW954To8L":3},"type":"background","data":{"description":"<p>The social hierarchy of the Eternal City is divided into classes determined not only by species and birth, but also by wealth and power. The classes are grouped into low, common and high castes. The higher a character&rsquo;s caste, the more wealth, influence and resources she is likely to command. Outside this system are the casteless, a segment not considered part of the social hierarchy. Characters always begin as casteless but can gain ranks within the low and common castes by spending character points. Different castes interact following strict social conventions and codes of conduct.</p>\n<p>As players spend points to acquire caste rankings, the character&rsquo;s starting funds and social standing increases.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>(0):&nbsp;KALBI - Kalbi are casteless, with no place or status in the </strong><strong>social hierarchy. They do the work that no one else wants </strong><strong>and are considered filthy, worthless and barred from most </strong><strong>districts and areas of the city. The literal meaning of Kalbi </strong><strong>is &ldquo;dog&rdquo;.</strong></p>","cost":0},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"dm3lJz5IA7BavXNq"}
